title: Area Two: Social and Emotional Development
subject: Early Learning and Development Standards (2021-)

document.title: VIRGINIA’S EARLY LEARNING & DEVELOPMENT STANDARDS (ELDS): BIRTH-FIVE LEARNING GUIDELINES

1D35E9D505194CE69A2677B281B79A46.description:
Uses problem-solving
strategies independently
or with adult prompting
when feeling angry or
frustrated (e.g., asks peer
to trade toys because they
want the one-of-a-kind
toy)

CC495C139723403994E34B14C152D3FE.description:
Expresses feelings
and needs in conflict
situations (e.g., “I’m
feeling upset because you
have the truck I need for
my racetrack.”)

83E1544DE2E04FC0B6C6B9EE6FEB683E.description:
Engages in
prosocial behavior
such as cooperating,
compromising, turntaking, and resolving
social conflict

3CCE399A19764539893265B149169F8B.description:
Uses problem-solving
strategies with adult
assistance (e.g., waits turn
after adult reminds them
how many children can
be in art area)

3AB3D71AC3B348DEADEADCD3D3336185.description:
Identifies and describes
common social problems
and may suggest some
solutions

640AB8F6BBA6407CA1E5A5BEC38A0558.description:
Begins to solve social
problems when facilitated
by an adult

02032425333E4C9BBE35679EDC505A64.description:
Builds on cooperative
play, communication,
and working memory
skills by engaging in
dramatic play with
several other children,
each taking on a
particular role in a shared
theme

DE8C5FBA08A745CAAC50251C489F1C20.description:
Includes familiar
adults in dramatic play

359C0C44130C4590A4AAC2EFD6630976.description:
Begins to engage in
cooperative play, playing
with a few other children
to carry out familiar roles

6FE2746B48384D7CB53C64ECC6394BD7.description:
Engages in associative
play (e.g., playing in
housekeeping with each
child assuming individual
roles)

8A39D2848DC94C7EBD84F501D3902DFE.description:
Plays simple games
(e.g., Simon Says/
Follow the Leader, Hide
and Seek or the Hokey
Pokey) led by familiar
adults

826410ACF6564EEDB69E473394B95914.description:
Engages in parallel
play, playing near or
beside other children
using similar materials
(e.g. playing in the sand
box using shared objects)

4E9DC49A0AA14123B2CAA6F2910DF84B.description:
Pretends to talk on toy
phone with familiar adult

A3D35BECBAEA4AEE8C805B909405E1F7.description:
Engages in solitary
play, watching other
children nearby while
continuing to play alone
(e.g., putting a puzzle
together or stacking
blocks)

1AC4BD5474A94FDFB45B14227DE81275.description:
Observes playful
actions of familiar
adults and imitates them

D5190A7A68844D5CB73B99163C641C3A.description:
Imitates simple
actions (e.g., claps hands
together, covers eyes
with hands)

D003657962E34BBB848921A2C2E6A39F.description:
Begins to engage
in solitary play with
materials, and observes
other people’s use of
objects

DA81B2560B944AC39D578C2ED5C2CCE6.description:
Plays social games
like peek-a-boo with a
familiar adult

E7B6077A62A64702B7C28947AD8E3E23.description:
Engages in solitary play
when exploring toys and
safe objects in indoor
and outdoor settings

74B71FF72AF646939DBDE0162CFA25AC.description:
Engages in unoccupied
play, practicing
movements of their arms,
hands, legs, feet, and head
(e.g., when safely situated
on the floor or in a crib)

2E914E6AAE5446CBA57D3150E4DC31C3.description:
Responds to the needs
of others and tries to help
others with simple tasks

3BE8A1CF61854742B7166F643EB874BF.description:
Plays with peers in
a coordinated manner
including assigning
roles, materials, and
actions (e.g., sets up and
assigns roles in restaurant
in dramatic play area)

34A423DF8C854A68A83DFB663B3F4551.description:
Demonstrates strategies
for participating in social
play with peers (e.g., asks
to join in game or brings
new item to add to
existing play)

7EBEF797730840BE9248D0BFB13C2FBA.description:
Engages in shared
activities or play with
shared toy or material

07ED4304D7CD42A48934B22B06FB7DFD.description:
Expresses interest in
participating in a group
activity by initiating or
responding

7B16508A17C9448485D2F040A461A46F.description:
Makes friends and
is able to name friends
when asked by an adult
or others

B30C19E6AA47462CB1AE43A07207EF32.description:
Shows preference for
particular playmates, such
as greeting friends by
name

D9375F4D7C9740CF897C2DEF63002140.description:
Builds social
relationships and becomes
more connected to other
children (e.g., has a
favorite friend at library
story time)

392F8E45081544D285821BAC2DDDA151.description:
Begins to initiate
interactions with other
children in shared play
activities

9169C79910524680B2735F83FB4EE492.description:
Responds to others’
questions in social
interactions with words
or actions

E34A661D495D4F2FAA5ECC3AD8B54B51.description:
Interacts with a few
children on shared
activities and understands
simple social interaction
rules (e.g., “your turn” or
“my turn”)

298DD32058F9418C813FEF4F5FF41C3C.description:
Plays alongside peers
and engages in simple
turn-taking (e.g., takes
turns on the slide at the
playground)

240A3FADFE77419497870B747B39D82E.description:
Enjoys playful
interactions and social
exchange games

6A29A2DB7FAB4255B622AB991A1938DE.description:
Interacts with a few
children on similar
activities (e.g., runs
after a child or plays
next to other children)

34B620B46BCA45BAB66A06FB5370D9CC.description:
Interacts with a few
children on a regular
basis, knows some of
their names, knows their
likes or dislikes

8F181A8AE1B542B18B8FE62533FB2949.description:
Participates in
simple back-and-forth
interactions with another
child

286C0D1896714C75A7DE6B5B00E2075D.description:
Interacts with a familiar
child in simple back-andforth exchanges (e.g.,
makes similar sounds)

F396236BFB36459BBE3BA1D4FB77B355.description:
Shows interest in peers
who are playing nearby
and interacts with them
briefly

7B5E9C1DC2D445829E53BB16BAC03999.description:
Recognizes familiar
others by making sounds,
facial expressions, or
behavior (e.g., reaches up
arms, or touches others’
face)

4435A4CE80D0425587401B326E6A826A.description:
Notices peers by
looking, touching, or
making sounds directed
toward the child (e.g.,
while lying on a blanket
close to them)

67EC53BCFDC2418E83BEAA786F1F0386.description:
Comfortable with
being with less familiar
adults in a safe setting
(e.g., engages with visitor
to home or classroom)

EA33C7868C5A477C8E1855072FBFD3A1.description:
Shows enjoyment
in interactions with
trusted adults while also
demonstrating skills in
separating from these
adults

F654AC8F85264560A89B9B7A286A180F.description:
Begins to interact with
less familiar adults (e.g.,
substitute educator or
neighbor)

5B6D3300B19B4EF8A4522C52D60A3193.description:
Develops positive
relationships and interacts
comfortably with familiar
adults

B837123B844D44CF9B28B05A1910D713.description:
Looks to or seeks
familiar adults for
comfort when distressed
or tired

04A512CF776A4727865F3B98DD74E996.description:
Engages in positive
interactions in a wide
variety of situations with
familiar adults

003164B1FC75410E82D85D4AF23CBD93.description:
Imitates and attempts
to please familiar adults
(e.g., puts plates on table
before lunch)

21DAFE4F68F544FA8A421CB55DE6B5B1.description:
Uses different words
or signs to refer to self
and others (e.g., joyously
shouts “titi!” when sees
aunt)

5FE25F0032C247FD8DF3FDFFCC00A5FE.description:
Continues to need the
security of a trusted adult;
asks for help, if needed,
in verbal and non-verbal
ways (e.g., returns to
familiar adult when at the
playground)

605E9FB7C806407D8375861E8F30C99E.description:
Expresses joy and
mutual enjoyment in
interactions with familiar
adults (e.g., giggles
during peek-a-boo

888082B8EEDE4A349B55B791A772AED2.description:
Reacts or may become
distressed when separated
from familiar adults

223EAC36586C49E3AF686C3CB258D025.description:
Looks to familiar adults
for emotional support
and encouragement

A83B15566D0149F087EC791CEE495151.description:
Needs additional
comforting (e.g.,
swaddling in a blanket
when being held by an
adult)

3CC64419E5E544AD83485C70B32D8A3B.description:
Develops trust and
attachment toward
significant adults (e.g.,
stops crying when
familiar caregiver picks
child up)

7D4993F363144519AEB34B9BA45AB057.description:
Responds differently to
familiar and unfamiliar
adults

D34F1B472DDB41428263BBFBC3F4480C.description:
Begins to understand
the reasons for others’
emotions and responds
appropriately (e.g., a
child comforts a peer
who is upset that they
have to clean up their
toys)

7EEA998F27D241CA9ADA943479B481D1.description:
Begins to recognize
the emotions of peers
and responds with
empathy and compassion

F3D40DD6A85240D8A90DAC4E2C7BF8C3.description:
Shows care and
concern for others,
including comforting
others in distress

A75E97E385624553B2DEE931282A953C.description:
Relates complex
emotions to self and
others (e.g., sees a friend
is sad and offers a toy to
share)

15A75F70B61E4B52A132934253C69E0F.description:
Recognizes the needs
of others and responds
appropriately, with
support from adults (e.g.,
asks Abraham to play
after the teacher points
out he is by himself)

D6CA431445494D2DB9B3D2C5167132DE.description:
Expresses empathy
toward adults who are
sad by comforting them
with words or actions

C5AD7610C8BC4978B375F34704BA9B05.description:
Expresses empathy
toward other children
who are crying by
showing concerned
attention; tries to comfort
them with words or
actions

DDAA010EEA8946B7A380075617FDBF54.description:
Tries to comfort
another child or an adult
who is upset (e.g., brings
a comfort object, pats
the person on the back)

17B6DC5A5C6640A59790DA118EC07A8A.description:
Responds to others'
emotional expressions,
often by sharing an
emotional reaction
(e.g., looks sad when
another child is crying)

4A0EF10B9BED433D91B4C35C39CABBCC.description:
Looks attentively when
others show they are
happy, sad, or fearful by
their facial expressions,
voices, or actions

3C37982E684F4FC1BBD87FBF302EC531.description: Showing care and concern for others

FF7091E4D3F746B29050DCF7573F38F5.description:
Exhibits emotional
control with or without
adult support (e.g.,
follows group activities
although upset)

E62BC08ECC124902829612C180D3D3F6.description:
Increasingly uses
a variety of strategies
to self-soothe or solve
problems (e.g., goes to
a quiet area or uses a
fidget toy when upset)

4A7980B643044181986F526A72AAD6A6.description:
Begins to understand
the impact of their
emotional behavior
(e.g., asks to join in peer
play rather than angrily
grabbing toy)

08503330F3B44D63A210A90B4FC06D68.description:
Begins to demonstrate
acceptable reaction to
situations (e.g., does
not shout when upset)

D32526DE9B9744A59B6824E2B1796184.description:
Begins to respond to
an adult’s cues about
regulating their emotions
(e.g., “The slide looks
scary, but I think you can
do it.”)

8C6D0A6434274C3B8EDA709232732CE4.description:
Seeks caregiver
support when feeling
overwhelmed by
emotion; may reject
support

B99E63FBB3B34C429C67DDC328E6A0D4.description:
Accepts adult
suggestions for managing
feelings by themselves

1DA680F41201404982AE94CF0A9598AE.description:
Engages in pretend
play to manage
uncertainty and fear (e.g.,
comforts stuffed animal
and puts on Band-Aid
after a “fall” or “cut”)

7AEAEA6E7268454CA118CDFB766E485B.description:
Uses caregiver’s facial
cues, voice tones, or
other body language
to assist in novel and
uncertain situations (e.g.,
hides behind parent until
encouraged to interact
with an unfamiliar
person)

967C400343CA4F64B9B5E204F28F50E3.description:
Self-soothes more
effectively (e.g., sucks
thumb, holds favorite
toy)

5936344AE9DB4C4E89D79BA491D6A0DD.description:
Uses preferred adult to
help soothe

1F5F4FECF8B74DFFB5A02C247A82F95E.description:
Seeks and accepts help
when needed

3A97904CDB68487584C10C837A5DC68C.description:
Demonstrates
confidence in meeting
own needs

CF3EFC568E8B4B7F92EDC4039B681AA1.description:
Uses appropriate
communication skills
when expressing
needs, wants, and
feelings (e.g., uses an
appropriate method of
communication to tell
adults when they are
hungry)

4E27CA019FFE466982E5F18FBD62AD28.description:
Communicates wants
and needs verbally or
through alternative
communication (e.g.,
“pick me up” or raises up
arms)

8DED007FF4C145A6BDDE70C2FD403243.description:
Uses verbal
and nonverbal
communication to
signal the need for their
caregiver (e.g., calls
by name, crawls into
a familiar adult’s lap)

AFE4B69CC5694566BD3044D9EE89C7AB.description:
Communicates with a
wide range of signals as
crying diminishes (e.g.,
smiles, gestures, uses
words)

6DE0C71949BC4EEFB91358EF6EAFA80B.description:
Signals for needs
(e.g., cries when
hungry, arches back in
discomfort)

FDB12DAFB41E4F1EA63A2C9AAAF057F3.description:
Uses words and
respectful language to
express thoughts and
emotions (e.g., “I’m
frustrated because Jay
won’t let me play” or
“I’m excited to play with
my cousin Santiago
tomorrow.”)

74E338AD4759422A9BBC465822B226BF.description:
Begins to recognize
and express own
emotions using words
or visuals rather than
actions (e.g., uses a
communication board
to point to picture of sad
face)

EF957FC2F87546CA9CC3D40941814452.description:
Expresses feelings that
are appropriate to the
situation

31708DE004264C698D5CB6156AB2CFBA.description:
Begins to express
complex emotions such
as pride, gratitude,
embarrassment, shame,
and guilt

2D9EBD4EE0344E37802D840BA2DF32EC.description:
Demonstrates an
emotional response to a
situation (e.g., throws toy
because told to clean up;
smiles and cheers when
it is time to go outside)

4C609D6F36D94E689FBAA39C4BE38AB3.description:
Uses movement or
facial expressions to
show an emotion (e.g.,
jumps up and down or
shows wider smiles when
excited, stomps feet when
upset, shows bigger
eyes when surprised)

DC84DACB114D4E0DA408B3C76D0FB5AA.description:
Uses gestures and
symbolic actions to
demonstrate feelings and
needs (e.g., lays head
on caregiver’s lap when
tired)

96570793E1B0482BA2E8A6D995AC7324.description:
Recognizes and
expresses emotion
toward a familiar person
(e.g., shows emotion
by hugging a sibling)

174D81124A854B6D818A7C88B7F920CD.description:
Begins to
spontaneously make
emotional gestures and
facial expressions that
match the situation (e.g.,
happiness, sadness, anger,
fear)

F845340FFAE74ECAAD63113EC179420E.description:
Expresses feelings
through facial
expressions, body
movements, crying
and vocalizing, often
depending on adults
for emotional comfort

AE3B20B0C20F4E13B82F525910AC6C74.description:
Communicates how
other children or adults
may be feeling and why
(e.g., states that a peer is
sad because their toy was
taken away)

6173E6562DF4404C806B63B87130DECE.description:
Begins to recognize
their own emotions
before reacting (e.g.,
pauses and takes deep
breath when mad)

EBFB196EAEDC4A4EA36A87657C7849EB.description:
Identifies complex
emotions in a book,
picture, or on a person’s
face (e.g., frustrated,
confused, excited)

A2062206BBD24EADA1FF6F44BB73C134.description:
Recognizes emotions
of others (e.g., "mama
sad," "papa happy")

5395497A3F6842B6979FB07832BAE563.description:
Recognizes and labels
own feelings with adult
support

9D97BC962437426DADDD810DD8BC6346.description:
Imitates emotions of
others (e.g., pats a child
or adult when upset)

2B38BDBAD42947F1A59F3D2EB6404C7B.description:
Begins to have a
greater awareness of own
emotions (e.g., says or
gestures “no” to refuse,
babbles or laughs when
happy)

9A0ACB1AA1E14E1D9DD56AC1704209D3.description:
Shows a range
of emotions (e.g.,
shares in wonders,
amazement, delight,
and disappointment)

5473A560C10C4239A1D3E7B2938C20A7.description:
Responds to
interactions from familiar
caregiver (e.g., smiles
when caregiver smiles,
turns head when hears
familiar voice)

36714DFDEDFD4E91BC5A40966B568D10.description:
Watches, observes, and
listens to adults and other
children

BE5397F0134F463483D909F11987AA41.description: Seeing and naming emotions in self and others

AC4A58033E8B467CA5341A5BA5ACCF8B.description:
Asks for support from
adults only when needed

0BB8F27878564014B8998261D4DD549D.description:
Acts independently
in unfamiliar settings
with unfamiliar adults

1CFBFDED426B434E9A4F4FD72E2B55C1.description:
Asks for help from
adults when needed, but
may prefer to complete
tasks independently

4212E107A4D64F8F9FD8D709A2CB0369.description:
Transitions into
unfamiliar settings with
assistance of familiar
adults

7144B266003845E8A8A435BCE03097A6.description:
Knows and states
independent thoughts
(e.g., “I do it myself.”)

F9239DA26D4C41A79EEA0767064F93B3.description:
Asks for help from
familiar adults, but may
push away and refuse
help

B1B32C70902845C6BD8E8FC6CBC18752.description:
Shows signs of security
and trust when separated
from familiar adults

E6346B0B0E214BE49A78F6E922B67001.description:
Asks for help from
familiar adults but may
attempt to complete parts
of tasks independently

A7686F936C5042CB811FB97B431127E8.description:
Shows anxiety upon
separation from primary
caregiver and/or familiar
adults

8F42654464F6485184E7313F208C8FB9.description:
Relies on familiar adults
for help or assistance

BE4975AE2B10490DA91BD1581E36B660.description:
Becomes calm when
needs are met

720AC1A4DB3D4D2CB49A9CDBDFEC447C.description:
Relies on familiar adults
to meet all basic needs

756E16DDEFF1465695E4384537E2D722.description:
Uses facial expressions
and body movements
to express comfort
or discomfort (e.g.,
turns head away when
no longer hungry)

F90D24BB98724E41A22DDB3D2C53ABD0.description:
Exhibits confidence in
performance (e.g., “Look
how high I jumped.”)

0A38ABC04F144C6C9F9ED4FAE73016ED.description:
Shows positive self-identity (e.g., “I am a
smart girl”)

4DFD6EA9AA66480EB6B2E198AD634BBC.description:
Begins to experiment
with their own potential
(e.g., sees how high
they can climb on the
playground equipment
or sees how fast they
can complete a task)

CDA193DA3DE54C569D2B9F101D0375F5.description:
Demonstrates new
skills and abilities to
others

EBD66D50346D4915850BE7FF950D3A39.description:
Expresses likes and
dislikes, including
favorite foods, colors, or
activities

D7EFED41C9944E518C02D0B60E4CE3F3.description:
Performs the tasks
requested of them and
may initiate tasks on their
own

90F918BFE138463E8460F6BC6D8DD92C.description:
Begins to recognize
own abilities; is aware of
self and own preferences

938CD26B2179459B9111DB093E646677.description:
Shows awareness of
being seen by others
such as repeating an
action when someone is
watching

3376B250630640A5B5F7FEB7FCF59DA9.description:
Shows likes and
dislikes consistent with
the family’s cultural
expectations (e.g., happily
eats the curry mashed
vegetables and signs
“more”)

E4FD9A7B08894E988562A3E9138899B6.description:
Smiles or is comforted
when a trusted caregiver
speaks to them

83C9F79F3062479DA224CAB4B3CBBFE6.description:
Describes a larger
range of individual
characteristics
and interests and
communicates how these
are similar or different
from those of other
people

B4F2B09560AD40758EFFFB46F9005336.description:
Shares other
identifying information
(e.g., parent’s name)

34DC8DE6D2504A608F94DD8E113F5E68.description:
Positively identifies self
as a member of a specific
culture or group that
fits into a larger world
picture

67DDB5285A244B42A42E5BCC5DD19C0D.description:
Describes themselves
(e.g., talks about self in
terms of looks, gender,
family, and interests)

7FBF241C8519431D8678BB0828AF0506.description:
Describes their physical
characteristics, behavior,
and abilities positively
(e.g., tells a peer,
“My hair is curly and
beautiful.”)

3F563B3EF5FC41C588E68B46DE32FC26.description:
Uses own first and
family (last) name

B49F1991F91C4C1BA003BCCC35235289.description:
Demonstrates
awareness of self as a
unique individual (e.g.,
refers to favorite shirt or
boots)

517FA8D62B20483B8191D628A9F9E7D3.description:
Indicates likes and
dislikes when asked

DB338C25558D4002946B412B550A73B9.description:
Describes own physical
characteristics and
behaviors

E8B828C853CD44798A989E513ECA8975.description:
Shows awareness of
being part of a family
and a larger community
(e.g., identifies siblings in
family photo)

7A753DD943234906847FE1734F976E80.description:
Shows awareness of
one's own thoughts,
feelings, and preferences
(e.g., child hits peer,
then says, “I’m mad”)

EACAEAC8860E48049065113715575786.description:
Discovers how
movement and gestures
can be used to relate to
others (e.g., reaches hand
out to grab a snack from
dad)

FDF09DBCFF5E407786B6D1214B200313.description:
Recognizes own name
(e.g., looks up, smiles,
or turns head toward a
person who is saying
their name)

6F9FE56D75A04C0AB5C4ED14A3839D15.description:
Displays personal
preferences and
individual temperament

A206E08DDF8C491484340C3944FF683E.description:
Learns about self by
exploring hands, feet,
body, and movement
